    public static final int help_formula_calculator = 0x7F07030D;  // string:help_formula_calculator "Almost in each field for entering numbers, you can 
                                                                   // enter a mathematical formula, after the equal sign, for example, in the search field 
                                                                   // enter \'= 2 + 2 * 3\', and the program will search for the result of the formula, 
                                                                   // that is, \'8\'.\nThe formula is a Lua expression. You can use all the available 
                                                                   // power of Lua in it.\n\nAll arithmetic operators Lua 5.3 are admissible - addition 
                                                                   // (+), subtraction (-), multiplication (*), division (/), division remainder (%), 
                                                                   // exponentiation (^), integer division (//), and so on.\nAlso available are bit operators 
                                                                   // - AND (&), OR (|), Exclusive OR (binary ~), NOT (unary ~), Shift to the right (>>), 
                                                                   // Shift to the left (<<). The order of action can be given by brackets.\nRead the 
                                                                   // Lua manual for a complete listing of available operations.\n\nIt is useful if you 
                                                                   // know how the value is coded in the game. For example, 29 rounds in one game can 
                                                                   // be found as \'= 29 ~ 444444\'. This is equivalent to 29 XOR 444444. In the video 
                                                                   // sample, the price was found 3888 through XOR with 444444, as \'= 444444 ~ 3888\'. 
                                                                   // After this, the replacement was made to \'= 444444 ~ 1\', which set the price to 
                                                                   // \'1\'. In another game, 125 gold is like \'= 125 * 10\'.\n\nNot all script functions 
                                                                   // are available in the formula calculator. Some functions are not available. If you 
                                                                   // do not have enough of them - write your script, instead of using a formula calculator, 
                                                                   // it is intended only for simple calculations. Available: part of the basic functions, 
                                                                   // \'bit32\', \'table\', \'string\', \'utf8\', \'math\', part of the \'os\' package. 
                                                                   // Packages \'debug\', \'package\', \'gg\', \'io\' are not available.\n\nWhen you write 
                                                                   // \'= 2 + 2 * 3\', the keyword \'return\' will be added before the formula: \'return 
                                                                   // 2 + 2 * 3\'. However, you can specify this word yourself in a formula if you need 
                                                                   // a complex formula.\nFor example, \'= a = 5; b = 7; return a * 4 + b * 8\' will be 
                                                                   // executed as \'a = 5; b = 7; return a * 4 + b * 8\'\n\nThe result of the formula 
                                                                   // calculator is a text string. The string can be any valid string for this input field.\nFor 
                                                                   // example, it may be a string for a group search or a range search. \'= a = 5; b = 
                                                                   // 7; return a .. \";\" .. b .. \":: 100\"\' is equivalent to \'5; 7 :: 100\'.\n\nFormula 
                                                                   // calculator does not work in scripts, there you can directly use Lua.\nWhen writing 
                                                                   // a script, the result of the formula calculation will be written to the file, not 
                                                                   // the formula itself.\n\nIf the formula is incorrect, you will receive an error message 
                                                                   // when you submit the form.\n\nWhen calculating, you must take into account the fact 
                                                                   // that calculations are carried out in the type that the first operand specifies. 
                                                                   // If it is an integer, then the result will be an integer.\nFor example, \'= 3/2\' 
                                                                   // is \'1\', and \'= 3.0 / 2\' is \'1.5\'.\n\nRegardless of the chosen locale, the 
                                                                   // formulas work in the English locale. This means that the decimal separator is always 
                                                                   // a dot (\'.\')."
    public static final int help_formula_calculator_title = 0x7F07030C;  // string:help_formula_calculator_title "Formula calculator"
